																	</h4>
								<div class="postinfo">
									Posted on 2008-11-26@10:26
																																			</div>
																@Familia: Using xrandr you can override which screen is the primary screen. The first output mentioned on the xrandr command will become the primary screen. Not that Gnome always puts your panels of the primary screen. So, to make the internal LVDS the primary one, use this:<br />
<br />
<pre>xrandr --output LVDS &lt;options&gt; --output VGA &lt;options&gt;</pre><br />
<br />
I do not know of a solution to the square desktop problem. I did lay out my monitors in such a way that I do not lose icons though. Gnome always tries to add icons on the bottom first. If you have two screens side-by-side, simply make sure that the one with the highest vertical resolution (in your case the 1280x1024) is the left most screen.
							</div>
